ambetov. It also explores paranoia as an instrument within contemporary Russian political rhetoric, as well as in pseudo-historical works. What stands out is the manner in which popular paranoia is utilized to express broadly shared fears not only of a long-standing anti-Russian conspiracy undertaken by the West, but also about the destruction of the country’s cultural and spiritual capital within this imagined "Russophobic" plot.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aConspiracies in literature. 0aConspiracies in popular culturezRussia (Federation)xHistoryy20th century. 0aConspiracies in popular culturezRussia (Federation)xHistoryy20thcentury. 0aParanoia in literature. 0aParanoia in popular culturezRussia (Federation)xHistoryy20th century. 0aParanoia in popular culturezRussia (Federation)xHistoryy20thcentury. 0aRussian fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aBekmambetov.  aDostoevsky.  aPelevin.  aProkhanov.  aRussia.  aapocalypticism.  aconspiracy theories.  aconspiracy, paranoia.  apost-Soviet cinema.  apost-Soviet culture.  apost-Soviet literature.  apost-catastrophe.  apost-modernism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753611440uhttps: